Naive Frequentists

2021-11-02

Logistic Regression (Initial Screening)

Assumptions:

  1. The outcome Death Event \(\sim Binomial(1, p)\), with the sample being IID.
    It is reasonable to assume that patients are independent with a constant probability of an event

  1. \(\mathbb{E}[\textit{Death Event}] = P(Death\;Event = 1) = p\) is linear on the logit scale \(\left(logit(p) = \frac{p}{1 - p}\right)\).
    We can assess this assumption through an analysis of the residuals. We will note any non-linear trends.

  1. ~10-20 events (\(Death\;Event = 1\)) per covariate.
    This assumption is almost met as we have 96 events and 12 covariates => 8 events per covariate. After doing an initial screening, we will reduce the number of predictors and be able to satisfy this requirement.

logi_fit = glm(data = dataset_wfactors, DEATH_EVENT ~ ., family = binomial())
pander(summary(logi_fit))

It appears that age, ejection_fraction, serum_creatinine, and time are the only covariates that are statistically significant at the standard 0.05 level. Before proceeding with further modeling, we will first check model diagnostics for this initial fit:

Distribution of Fitted values and Leverage (hat-values)

ggplot(dataset_wfactors, aes(logi_fit$fitted.values)) + geom_histogram() + ggtitle("p-hats") + xlab("p-hats")

ggplot(dataset_wfactors, aes(hatvalues(logi_fit))) + geom_histogram() + ggtitle("hat-values") + xlab("hat-values")

Cooks Distance

influencePlot(logi_fit, col = "red")

##     StudRes    Hat  CookD
## 61    0.793 0.3006 0.0136
## 132  -2.310 0.0838 0.0667
## 187   2.738 0.0112 0.0300
## 196   2.399 0.0250 0.0281
## 218   1.660 0.5231 0.2001

Observations 132, 187, and 196 only have large Studentized residuals, with their leverage and Cooks D. being small. Conversely, observation 61 has a small Studentized residual and Cooks D but a large leverage value. Likewise, observation 218 has a moderate Studentized residual and large leverage and Cooks D values.

Outlier Test

outlierTest(logi_fit)
## No Studentized residuals with Bonferroni p < 0.05
## Largest |rstudent|:
##     rstudent unadjusted p-value Bonferroni p
## 187     2.74            0.00618           NA

Not surprisingly, only observation 187 became a statistically significant outlier. This is because it has the largest studentized residual value.

Based on the above, it seems that 218 may be the most influential observation, while observation 187 is the most significant outlier. We will re-run the above analysis with these points removed and note any appreciable change in the coefficients:

Model with Influential Points 187 and 218 Removed

logi_fit_no_out = glm(data = dataset_wfactors[-c(187, 218), ], DEATH_EVENT ~ ., family = binomial())
pander(summary(logi_fit_no_out))

It seems that the coefficients for age and ejection_fraction increased, while the coefficients for serum_creatinine and time decreased. Moreover, the p-values for age, ejection_fraction, and serum_creatinine decreased (became more significant), while the p-value for time increased (became less significant).

Second logistic model: statistically significant predictors only

The only assumption that we will address is #3 since the distributional assumptions have not changed:

  1. ~10-20 events (\(Death\;Event = 1\)) per covariate.
    This assumption is now met as we have 96 events and 4 covariates => 24 events per covariate

logi_signi = glm(data = dataset_wfactors, 
                 DEATH_EVENT ~ age + ejection_fraction + serum_creatinine + time, family = binomial())
